  "created": "2025-10-15",
  "description": "Base Excision Repair (BER) in E. coli corrects non-bulky base lesions caused by oxidation, alkylation, or spontaneous deamination. The pathway begins with damage recognition by DNA glycosylases (e.g., UNG, MutM, MutY, AlkA) which cleave the N-glycosidic bond to create an abasic (AP) site. AP endonucleases (Nfo, Xth) then cleave the phosphodiester backbone, followed by gap-filling by DNA polymerase I and nick sealing by DNA ligase. The pathway includes both short-patch (single nucleotide) and long-patch (2-10 nucleotides) repair mechanisms. This flowchart illustrates the complete BER pathway from lesion recognition through strand restoration, including quality control and alternative pathways.",
  "id": "ecoli_base_excision_repair",
  "keywords": [
    "base excision repair",
    "ber",
    "dna glycosylases",
    "ap site",
    "dna polymerase i",
    "dna ligase",
